What is sudo?

sudo = Super User Do

sudo allows a normal user to execute commands with administrator (root) privileges.

Why do we use sudo?

Some tasks require admin permissions:

Install software
Create users
Delete users
Change ownership
Update packages
Restart services

Without sudo:

apt update

May fail with:

Permission denied

With sudo:

sudo apt update

Works successfully.

Real Examples

Create user:

sudo adduser devuser

Change owner:

sudo chown sandhya file.txt

Install package:

sudo apt install nginx
Interview Answer

sudo stands for Super User Do. It is used to execute commands with administrator privileges. We use sudo for tasks such as user management, package installation, permission changes, and system administration.

Project-Based Answer

During Linux user provisioning, I used sudo commands to create users, manage groups, assign permissions, and update ownership of files and directories.

One-Line Answer

sudo allows a normal user to perform administrative tasks with elevated privileges.
